	abstract = {Objective/Background: Subjective methods are often employed for sleep assessment due to their ease of use, but the results may not concur with objective findings. This discrepancy may be present in schizophrenia; however, limited data are available. We performed a secondary analysis to evaluate the agreement between 1-week actigraphy and sleep diaryderived parameters and factors that contribute to subjective-objective sleep discrepancy. Participants: 66 outpatients with schizophrenia (mean age = 44.08 years; 45.45\% males).
Methods: Agreement between subjective-objective parameters was assessed using two-way repeated measures ANOVA, Pearson’s correlation, and Bland-Altman plot. The magnitude of discrepancy was quantified using Cohen’s d. Pearson’s correlation was used to determine the significant factors of subjective-objective sleep discrepancy. Benjamini-Hochberg adjustment was performed to account for multiple testing.
