Results Overall, 727 patients were included (58.0\% males). A significant difference was found in SPI between non-OSA and OSA groups (p = 0.014). Mean SPI values significantly decreased as the OSA severity increased: without OSA (100.1 ± 40.9\%), mild OSA (95.1 ± 24.6\%), moderate OSA (93.5 ± 25.2\%), and severe OSA (90.6 ± 28.2\%), p = 0.036. Using logistic regression, increasing SPI was associated with a reduction in the likelihood of presenting any OSA (p = 0.018), moderate/severe OSA (p = 0.019), and severe OSA (p = 0.028). However, insomnia was not considered as an independent variable for the presence of any OSA, moderate/severe OSA, and severe OSA (all p-values {\textgreater} 0.05).
